item.title: knuckle buster
item.description:
this is a project im working on for fun its a 9 function joystick for pc
i wanted to design a non traditional joystick which the hand naturally integrated with

i was playing an online battle game using the mouse and keypad for control and i kept pushing the wrong key when things heated up
so i decided i wanted a simpler way to control and fire using a simple 5 button controller
4 direction and 1 fire button .the other function in the game will be added using magnetic
switches mounted under the controller so in all it will have10 function buttons
every thing can be controlled using one hand if this works out it should increase my reaction time
the controller itself is comprised of 2 parts. The micro switches were purchased on amazon
i designed a base to house my magnetic switches which will be activated when i move the controller over them by a magnet placed under the bottom i believe when done this will be a novel and fun way to play games ,once your muscle memory kicks in movement in game play should be pretty fluid .As the project progresses i will add the rest of the design along with parts list

item.title: Food Chain Automaton
item.description:
When given the task to expand your imagination and make something from yu mind become a reality Nathan and I reacted quickly and went to find inspiration quickly. We landed on something animal-related and some things looked a bit too simplistic for us so we took bits and pieces from everywhere and landed on the project we are happy to report you to now.

Our Project it and Animal Food Chain start with a tiny Goldfish getting chased by Penguin which is then getting chased by an Orca. We thought that this would captivate our level of engineering pretty well in the challenge aspect but we faced a lot more than we anticipated.

With our final project, it should look as though the animals are chasing each other/ running away from their predator.

All and all it was a very fun project to make and a great experience. I highly recommend you try and assemble this yourself.

item.title: EOTech Anti Reflective Device (ARD) Killflash (Improved Paddle)
item.description:
This is an ARD Anti Reflective Device for EOTech's line of holographic optics. It reduces glint and reflectivity off of the already anti-reflection coated glass on the face of the optic. It also serves as an extra protective measure for the glass against impact and scratches. This is an improved STL of a model that I found online a while back, whose paddle was too thick and made it difficult/impossible to equip on genuine EOTech brand models.

Print lattice side down, no supports, at 100% scale and 100% infill for best results. I also used PLA+ for durability. IF YOU ARE PRINTING WITH A GLASS BED (or any other particularly smooth surface bed), you will need to either sand the front of this device or spray it with some sort of FLAT spray paint, as the material off the print bed will be shinier than the glass on the optic itself, which would defeat the purpose of a "killflash."

Once printed, insert the paddle between the glass and the hood that hovers over it.

item.title: Piramide Mascota orgonica base 600x600
item.description:
Piramide con piezas huecas para ser rellenada por material orgánico que puede utilizarse como cama para las mascotas si se coloca.
La piramide se debe completar con relleno de material orgónico en todas las piezas.
El material orgónico consta de virutas de aluminio y arena de cuarzo con resina (poliamida o epoxy), todo mezclado al 33,33% de volumen.
Todas las piezas deben ir rellenas de material orgonico.
En las bases existen entradas y salidas para cable de toma de tierra.
Entre todos los extremos se pueden colocar tirantes (ya hay agujeros preparados para ello)

Para cualquier consulta, por favor contactar en privado.

item.title: Artillery X2 - Genius Pro Bl touch mount (waggster)
item.description:
A quick remix of the X2 waggster fan shroud mount by Dannsantos (Thanks for doing it) to take off the fan shroud allowing the use of the original fan and replacment BL touch or 3d touch on the X2 or Genius Pro. This will fit the X2 / Genius Pro and allow the blue plastic cover to be used.

printed with support from bed. 70% infill.
You will need to change the offset for the BL touch.
That is relatively simple.
Download Prontaface, use the blue cable from the black bag. connect cable to computer and the side of the printer, the printer will start (using the 5v rom the usb) check the com port top left on Prontaface and change connection to 115200. connect to printer. on right side it will say connected.

M851 X28 Y-33
then type M500 to save it to eeprom.
then M501 use active parameters
That will be the new BL touch flashed into eeprom

basic Youtube about setting up Prontaface; https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=sbIwHGrOzUM

item.title: Texas Instruments Calculator Front Covers (TI-84 Plus, TI-84 Plus C, TI-90 Titanium, and similar)
item.description:
I needed a replacement cover for a TI-89 Titanium edition that I was selling on Facebook marketplace, so that the buyer would be satisfied. Luckily, I had another TI-84 calculator that still had its original cover so I could recreate one for my TI-89.

All of the measurements in this post are my own, so they could be not exact to the original part, but the printed part still works splendidly. I am going to include them, a short explanation, and the model files so you can more easily modify/make your own. It would be cool to see a TI calculator cover that had a hinge so the front cover folded open rather than coming entirely off.

The key measurements include:

For the rail/slot cross section profile

The distance from the calculator front keys to the to the far side of the cover slot.
    12.7 mm (0.50 in)
The size of the cover rail slot on the calculator.
    2.0 mm (0.079 in)
The depth of the cover rail slot on the calculator.
    1.27 mm (0.05 in)
The width of the calculator (from left to right).
    84 mm (3.31 in)
Rail start from bottom of the case ~40 mm and a rail length of 79 mm.

For the case profile

The distance from foot to head on the front of the calculator
    187 mm (7.36 in)
The curvature of the calculator side cross section
    Measured to be 10 mm (0.39 in).
The curvature of the calculator foot front cross section.
    Assumed tangent to both edges, and measured a foot horizontal length of 34 mm (1.34 in).

I created a rectangular profile with an offset from the calculator body of 0.2 mm, and designed a rail from the side of the rectangular profile with similar tolerances and a 60 degree angle so that it would not need supports.

I went with a 2.2 mm shell thickness. I also created one with an angular side profile so all support are eliminated by not having the curved 10 mm surface.

EDIT

Later, I found a TI-84 model on GrabCad so I am linking it here. There is also a case on there I saw too, but I did not like it very much.
item.author: Ostella3d

item.title: RC Plane snow skis
item.description:
Skis for your planes so you can fly in the frozen winter! I live in Maine, so flying in the wintertime means snow. Obviously, skis had to happen. I've tweaked these to the point that I'm pretty happy with them. They look scale-ish and fly well. The only thing I'd say is that when landing, you might need more up elevator than you're used to.

They are designed to be held on with rubber bands over the wheels and "sprung" with either a cut rubber band or elastic thread for the front and back to keep the skis at the correct attitude. Be sure to take them off when you're done flying so the rubber bands don't deform your tires.

I printed these in PEGP but I can't see how it wouldn't work in PLA. Supports are only for the lugs that the rubber bands fit over to keep it on the wheel. I've been flying with these for two winters now and they work really well. These were designed to fit 70mmx20mm wheels (2.75 in x .75 in) but can be scaled easily to fit smaller wheels.
